And at the very end, as he goes backstage... Endo is greeted and congratulated by the entire roster. Even Take & Ueno, who are whispering to each other like the mean girls that they are, clap for him.
He takes his place at their center.
Finally, his dream has come true.

Endo screams after him "I hate you, Take-chan!", perhaps the voice of his younger self ringing out, but he's smiling. That entanglement of love and loathing between them is too big to be resolved just yet, but maybe one day it can be. They are equals now.

And while Take's pride is too wounded to acknowledge him strongly, while the pain between them is still too big for reconciliation... Take does finally acknowledge him. He refuses his handshake, but does raise his hand for the victory before leaving wordlessly.

If Endo wants to beat Take, then like Take, he has to be himself. He can take inspiration from others, but ultimately, just imitating them won't take him to that level. It's with his own strength, his own moves, 1 from his Damnation time, 1 from his youth, that he finally wins.

And he still does. Endo misses and Take immediately counters with the V-Trigger-inspired Za-Hi, his heart perhaps connecting those moves. He can't be Ibushi, he can't be the naturally talented, effortlessly interesting, eternally free-spirited and beloved legend of DDT.

But even still... As the match goes on and everything in his arsenal proves insufficient, what Endo finds when he digs as deep as he can dig...
Is the Phoenix Splash. The finisher of Kota Ibushi, the man Endo wanted to be the successor of and failed to ever measure up to.

A miniature re-enaction of his betrayal, a miniature rejection of an offer to go back to how they were all of those years ago. They can't go back. Too much has happened and they're different people now.

Eventually... for just a moment, he abandons his serious champion self and goes for the hig wiggle & Dusty punch that they would sometimes use back in their Happy Motel days. He hits and Endo counters... with the Crossface, Daisuke Sasaki's submission finisher.

Perhaps in desperation, perhaps because being together reminds them.
And Endo, who starts out trying to wrestle a true "heavyweight style match", to be like Take, moves more and more back to his high-flying core. And interestigly enough, Take joins him.

Endo survives by the skin of his teeth, but bit by bit, he slowly starts to chip away as his overwhelming opponent. And as the match goes on, both of them start reaching for the past, for moves from their early matches.

Hell, at the beginning, there is a whole extended sequence where Endo holds onto Take's wrists from the back like a lifeline, leaning his head against the guy's back, specifically denying him the ability to look at him. To judge him as not worthy.

And the match shows that dynamic. Take is a terrfiying mountain of strength who somehow comes back with an immense surge of energy every time you just think he's been staggered. Endo starts out with a plan, but as time goes on you see it devolve into pure desperation.

As someone lesser. Someone once dear, someone to be pitied or punished, maybe, but certainly not an equal.
This match was Endo's big chance. He had re-invented himself once again, claimed he was a different, stronger man, but this was his last & only chance to actually prove that

He and Take were chosen to be Ibushi's & Kenny's successors, but Take wouldn't even look at him as a serious rival anymore. He was an accessory.
And even betraying Take, rejecting him and hindering him at every opportunity didn't change the way the man saw him.
Endo, meanwhile, has his stare fixed on Take from the start. He was always in his shadow, the less naturally gifted, the less charismatic, the less interesting member of that tag team.

But deep down, he does want someone. He wants that connection that only comes from two people on equal footing leaving it all in the ring. That's the reason he's sometimes so rough with his own stablemates and Ueno in particular, he hopes they'll rise up to meet him someday.

Right from the build-up.
Take is the undefeatable god of DDT. A man so beyond anyone else in the promotion that, as he says, he's not looking at anyone else. There's no-one he sees as a worthy rival, so all he looks to is himself and how far he can push his own limits.

God, Take vs Endo was just... so good. So, so good.
I've got to ramble about it a little now, my apologies.

I think the piece of Umineko fanart that I would most be willing to pay for existing is both layers of that scene transparently overlaying each other.

Because perhaps that's the only thing that can make him feel anything at this point.
Who is he? He's not a leader anymore. He's not a champion by his own power. He's not a friend or part of a trio. He's only 36 and already being forgotten. All he has left his spite.

And all that remains for him is to destroy everything he loved, from the former Damnation members who try to escape his influence to everyone who reminds him of the people who started it all. He doesn't just want to beat them, he wants to hurt & humiliate them as badly as he can.

He tried to become a better person once and he failed, because that sort of thing isn't easy. And unlike Kenny, no one is coming to help him out of this destructive spiral. The only friend he is left now is one who was created by him and cannot think for himself.

It's really tragic, because Sasaki, too, was screaming out through ever more heinous actions "Won't you come back to me?" at those two people who were once special to him.

It's a combination of how afraid I'm of things dying and vanishing and how well I know that they do and must change, wither and be reborn. Legacy is my way of dealing with that. And that's why I spend a ton of money collecting out-of-print DVDs of a Japanese Comedy Promotion, lol

I think that's beautiful.
The "passing of the torch" is a bit of a cliché, of course. It can feel very hollow if its not done right. But it was important to me when Kagetsu passed on her dream of changing the world of joshi wrestling to Asuka/Veny and it's important to me here.

But for the much smaller DDT, those two were supernovas, if you'll forgive the sneaky FF7 reference. They completely changed the landscape there forever and their impact will inevitably carried on by this generation of their stars and the one in turn inspired by them.

New Japan, meanwhile, seems like this ancient immovable monolith. Every new legend created within it adorns it further, but almost never do they... change it, if that makes sense. The history it is built on is not their history and they cannot hold that same importance to it.

I feel like AEW is Hangman's promotion. It's the gift the Elite made for him. And there is something beautiful to that. But the consequence of how careful they were to not overshadow him is that there never really was a passing of the torch. There was the lighting of a new one.

Now, they left an impact on AEW and New Japan, too, of course. I honestly don't think there's anywhere they could go without leaving something behind there.
But in these larger promotions, where legends are crowded, I've just never felt that same deep love & reverence for them.

Even small-scale. In March, when comedy wrestler Hirata did a sketch that involved him thinking about the ultimate, most devastating move a wrestler could do... what he came up with was the Phoenix Splash.
While I ofc have my criticisms of the promotion, too, it's undeniable.

A faction whose wink-and-a-nod closeness (with the occasional love confession) very much follows on the trail they blazed, who still do both of their moves in big matches and whose most well-known member is Takeshita, a man Kenny directly chose to pass his torch to.

Because they're kind of already doing it. Both of them are still present in the promotion, through the profound impact DAMNATION, a faction founded specifically because of their absence, left on a huge part on the roster. And through T37K, of course.

Time to post feelings during a time window when no-one will see them, lol

I always pretend I'm above getting into petty arguments but then instead I just write overlong overthought vagueposts, lol

Obviously, when a big promotion does give the time and effort to a storyline, it can be extraordinarly amazing. I adore the entire story of the Elite. But not everyone can be given that treatment and if too many standout talents sign, some will fall to the wayside.

Like, I get the impulse, but really thinking about it... Would Itoh, for instance, get the heartwarming shonen-protagonist's journey she has in TJPW in AEW? Would Take be able to build a stable as beloved & complexly connected as the sauna club? They wouldn't. There'd be no time.

I actually much prefer wrestlers be stars with big, consistant storylines in smaller promotions rather than being in a big promotion that has no time to give them. I'm always a little uncomfortable when people demand that everyone sign with the same place...
